Task 1: Set Up Remote Logging with rsyslog
Subtask 1.1: Verify rsyslog Installation and Status
First, let's check if rsyslog is installed and running on your system.

# Check if rsyslog is installed
dpkg -l | grep rsyslog

# Check rsyslog service status
sudo systemctl status rsyslog

# If not running, start the service
sudo systemctl start rsyslog
sudo systemctl enable rsyslog
Subtask 1.2: Understand rsyslog Configuration Structure
Examine the main rsyslog configuration file and directory structure.

# View the main configuration file
sudo cat /etc/rsyslog.conf

# List additional configuration files
ls -la /etc/rsyslog.d/

# Create a backup of the original configuration
sudo cp /etc/rsyslog.conf /etc/rsyslog.conf.backup
Subtask 1.3: Configure rsyslog as a Log Server
Configure rsyslog to receive logs from remote sources (simulating remote logging on the same machine).

# Edit the rsyslog configuration
sudo nano /etc/rsyslog.conf
Add or uncomment the following lines in the configuration file:

# Enable UDP syslog reception
$ModLoad imudp
$UDPServerRun 514
$UDPServerAddress 127.0.0.1

# Enable TCP syslog reception
$ModLoad imtcp
$InputTCPServerRun 514
$InputTCPServerBindRuleset remote
Create a custom configuration file for remote logging:

sudo nano /etc/rsyslog.d/10-remote.conf
Add the following content:

# Remote logging configuration
$template RemoteHost,"/var/log/remote/%HOSTNAME%/%PROGRAMNAME%.log"

# Log remote messages to separate files
if $fromhost-ip != '127.0.0.1' then ?RemoteHost
& stop

# Create template for local simulation
$template LocalRemote,"/var/log/remote/localhost/%PROGRAMNAME%.log"
if $programname startswith 'remote-' then ?LocalRemote
& stop
Subtask 1.4: Create Remote Log Directory Structure
Set up the directory structure for remote logs:

# Create remote log directories
sudo mkdir -p /var/log/remote/localhost
sudo chown syslog:adm /var/log/remote/localhost
sudo chmod 755 /var/log/remote/localhost

# Restart rsyslog to apply changes
sudo systemctl restart rsyslog

# Verify rsyslog is listening on port 514
sudo netstat -tulpn | grep :514
Subtask 1.5: Test Remote Logging Configuration
Test the remote logging setup by sending test messages:

# Send a test message using logger
logger -p local0.info "This is a test message from local system"

# Send a simulated remote message
logger -t remote-testapp -p local1.warning "This is a simulated remote application warning"

# Check if logs are being written
sudo tail -f /var/log/syslog &
sleep 2
logger -p user.notice "Testing user facility logging"
sleep 2
kill %1
Verify the remote logging is working:

# Check remote log files
sudo ls -la /var/log/remote/localhost/
sudo cat /var/log/remote/localhost/remote-testapp.log
Task 2: Use journalctl to View and Manage Logs
Subtask 2.1: Basic journalctl Commands
Learn the fundamental journalctl commands for viewing systemd journal logs.

# View all journal entries
journalctl

# View journal entries in real-time
journalctl -f

# View journal entries from the current boot
journalctl -b

# View journal entries from previous boot
journalctl -b -1

# View last 50 entries
journalctl -n 50
Subtask 2.2: Filter Logs by Service and Priority
Practice filtering logs using various journalctl options:

# View logs for a specific service
journalctl -u rsyslog

# View logs for systemd itself
journalctl -u systemd-journald

# View logs by priority (error level and above)
journalctl -p err

# View logs by priority (warning level and above)
journalctl -p warning

# View logs for a specific time range
journalctl --since "2024-01-01 00:00:00" --until "2024-12-31 23:59:59"

# View logs from the last hour
journalctl --since "1 hour ago"
Subtask 2.3: Advanced journalctl Filtering
Explore advanced filtering capabilities:

# View logs by process ID
journalctl _PID=1

# View logs by user ID
journalctl _UID=0

# View kernel messages
journalctl -k

# View logs with specific fields
journalctl -o verbose | head -20

# View logs in JSON format
journalctl -o json | head -5

# Follow logs for multiple services
journalctl -f -u rsyslog -u systemd-journald
Subtask 2.4: Generate Test Log Entries
Create various types of log entries to practice with journalctl:

# Generate different priority level messages
logger -p user.debug "Debug message for testing"
logger -p user.info "Info message for testing"
logger -p user.notice "Notice message for testing"
logger -p user.warning "Warning message for testing"
logger -p user.err "Error message for testing"
logger -p user.crit "Critical message for testing"

# Generate messages with different tags
logger -t webapp "Web application started successfully"
logger -t database "Database connection established"
logger -t security "Failed login attempt detected"
View the generated messages:

# View recent messages
journalctl -n 20

# Filter by specific tags
journalctl -t webapp
journalctl -t security

# Search for specific content
journalctl | grep -i "error"
journalctl | grep -i "failed"
Subtask 2.5: Journal Storage Management
Understand and manage journal storage:

# Check journal disk usage
journalctl --disk-usage

# View journal configuration
sudo cat /etc/systemd/journald.conf

# Vacuum old journal files (keep last 2 days)
sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=2d

# Vacuum journal files by size (keep last 100MB)
sudo journalctl --vacuum-size=100M

# Check disk usage after cleanup
journalctl --disk-usage
Task 3: Automate Log Rotation with logrotate
Subtask 3.1: Understand logrotate Configuration
Examine the existing logrotate configuration:

# View main logrotate configuration
sudo cat /etc/logrotate.conf

# List logrotate configuration files
ls -la /etc/logrotate.d/

# View rsyslog logrotate configuration
sudo cat /etc/logrotate.d/rsyslog
Subtask 3.2: Create Custom Log Files for Testing
Create custom log files to practice log rotation:

# Create a test application directory
sudo mkdir -p /var/log/testapp

# Create test log files
sudo touch /var/log/testapp/application.log
sudo touch /var/log/testapp/error.log
sudo touch /var/log/testapp/access.log

# Set proper ownership
sudo chown syslog:adm /var/log/testapp/*.log
sudo chmod 644 /var/log/testapp/*.log
Generate some log content:

# Create a script to generate log entries
cat << 'EOF' > /tmp/generate_logs.sh
#!/bin/bash
for i in {1..100}; do
    echo "$(date): Application log entry $i - Normal operation" | sudo tee -a /var/log/testapp/application.log > /dev/null
    echo "$(date): Access log entry $i - User accessed resource" | sudo tee -a /var/log/testapp/access.log > /dev/null
    if [ $((i % 10)) -eq 0 ]; then
        echo "$(date): Error log entry $((i/10)) - Minor error occurred" | sudo tee -a /var/log/testapp/error.log > /dev/null
    fi
done
EOF

chmod +x /tmp/generate_logs.sh
/tmp/generate_logs.sh
Subtask 3.3: Create Custom logrotate Configuration
Create a custom logrotate configuration for the test application:

sudo nano /etc/logrotate.d/testapp
Add the following configuration:

/var/log/testapp/*.log {
    daily
    rotate 7
    compress
    delaycompress
    missingok
    notifempty
    create 644 syslog adm
    postrotate
        /usr/lib/rsyslog/rsyslog-rotate
    endscript
}
Subtask 3.4: Test logrotate Configuration
Test the logrotate configuration before applying it:

# Test the configuration syntax
sudo logrotate -d /etc/logrotate.d/testapp

# Check current log file sizes
ls -lh /var/log/testapp/

# Force log rotation for testing
sudo logrotate -f /etc/logrotate.d/testapp

# Check the results
ls -lh /var/log/testapp/
Subtask 3.5: Configure Advanced Log Rotation
Create a more advanced logrotate configuration:

sudo nano /etc/logrotate.d/testapp-advanced
Add advanced configuration options:

/var/log/testapp/application.log {
    size 1M
    rotate 5
    compress
    delaycompress
    missingok
    notifempty
    create 644 syslog adm
    copytruncate
}

/var/log/testapp/error.log {
    weekly
    rotate 12
    compress
    delaycompress
    missingok
    notifempty
    create 644 syslog adm
    mail admin@localhost
    mailfirst
}

/var/log/testapp/access.log {
    daily
    rotate 30
    compress
    delaycompress
    missingok
    notifempty
    create 644 syslog adm
    sharedscripts
    postrotate
        echo "Access log rotated at $(date)" >> /var/log/testapp/rotation.log
    endscript
}
Subtask 3.6: Monitor and Verify Log Rotation
Set up monitoring for log rotation:

# Create a script to monitor log rotation
cat << 'EOF' > /tmp/monitor_rotation.sh
#!/bin/bash
echo "=== Log Rotation Status ==="
echo "Current log files:"
ls -lh /var/log/testapp/

echo -e "\n=== Logrotate Status ==="
sudo cat /var/lib/logrotate/status | grep testapp

echo -e "\n=== Recent Rotation Activity ==="
if [ -f /var/log/testapp/rotation.log ]; then
    cat /var/log/testapp/rotation.log
fi
EOF

chmod +x /tmp/monitor_rotation.sh
/tmp/monitor_rotation.sh
Test the advanced configuration:

# Generate more log content
/tmp/generate_logs.sh

# Force rotation with the advanced config
sudo logrotate -f /etc/logrotate.d/testapp-advanced

# Monitor the results
/tmp/monitor_rotation.sh
Integration and Verification
Comprehensive System Log Analysis
Perform a comprehensive analysis of the logging system:

# Create a log analysis script
cat << 'EOF' > /tmp/log_analysis.sh
#!/bin/bash
echo "=== System Log Analysis ==="
echo "1. Rsyslog Status:"
sudo systemctl status rsyslog --no-pager

echo -e "\n2. Journal Disk Usage:"
journalctl --disk-usage

echo -e "\n3. Recent System Errors:"
journalctl -p err --since "1 hour ago" --no-pager

echo -e "\n4. Log File Sizes:"
sudo du -sh /var/log/* 2>/dev/null | sort -hr | head -10

echo -e "\n5. Remote Log Status:"
if [ -d /var/log/remote ]; then
    sudo find /var/log/remote -type f -exec ls -lh {} \;
fi

echo -e "\n6. Logrotate Status:"
sudo logrotate -d /etc/logrotate.conf 2>&1 | grep -E "(error|warning)" || echo "No errors found"
EOF

chmod +x /tmp/log_analysis.sh
/tmp/log_analysis.sh
